Step 0 – Prerequisites (important)

Before running any kubectl command, you must have:

A running Kubernetes cluster
(use one of these):
Minikube (recommended for beginners)
Docker Desktop Kubernetes
A cloud cluster (AWS EKS / GKE / AKS)

👉 Check if Kubernetes is working:

kubectl version --client
kubectl get nodes

If you see nodes → ✅ you're ready

🚀 Step 1 – Create a Deployment

Run this in your terminal / command prompt:

kubectl create deployment myapp --image=nginx:latest

Now verify:

kubectl get deployments
kubectl get pods

👉 What happens:

Kubernetes creates a Deployment
It automatically creates a Pod running nginx
📈 Step 2 – Scale the Deployment
Scale UP to 3 pods:
kubectl scale deployment myapp --replicas=3

Check:

kubectl get pods

👉 You’ll see 3 pods running

Scale DOWN to 1 pod:
kubectl scale deployment myapp --replicas=1
🌐 Step 3 – Expose the Application
kubectl expose deployment myapp --port=80 --type=NodePort

Check service:

kubectl get services

👉 You’ll get something like:

myapp   NodePort   10.x.x.x   <port>
🔍 Access in Browser

If using Minikube:

minikube service myapp

Otherwise:

http://<node-ip>:<node-port>
🔎 Step 4 – Inspect & Debug
Describe a pod:
kubectl describe pod <pod-name>
View logs:
kubectl logs <pod-name>

To get pod name:

kubectl get pods
🧹 Step 5 – Cleanup
kubectl delete deployment myapp
kubectl delete service myapp
📄 Step 6 – Using YAML (Better Practice)
Create file: deployment.yaml

Paste this:

apiVersion: apps/v1
kind: Deployment
metadata:
  name: myapp
spec:
  replicas: 2
  selector:
    matchLabels:
      app: myapp
  template:
    metadata:
      labels:
        app: myapp
    spec:
      containers:
      - name: myapp
        image: nginx:latest
        ports:
        - containerPort: 80
Apply it:
kubectl apply -f deployment.yaml

Check everything:

kubectl get all
